<title>FRANCE: Microsoft says software piracy costs jobs.</title>
<headline>Microsoft says software piracy costs jobs.</headline>
<dateline>PARIS 1996-12-03</dateline>
<text>
<p>Microsoft Corp could have an additional $1.0 billion in sales in Europe were it not for sofware piracy, which is also costing jobs, Microsoft Europe president Bernard Vergnes said on Tuesday.</p>
<p>&quot;Software piracy in Europe is a significant blight on our industry and an entrenched problem that directly affects the long-term health of software developers, large and small,&quot; Vergnes told a news conference.</p>
<p>Piracy has broad implications for Europe, he added.</p>
<p>&quot;Software piracy is costing thousands of legitimate jobs in Europe and hurting consumers and honest businesses. High piracy rates also discourage innovation and hurt competitiveness in this important growth sector,&quot; he added.</p>
<p>Microsoft said it reached a settlement on Tuesday with an Italian businessman who owns a computer company in Milan and will pay 100 million lira for having sold 1,000 copies of counterfeit Microsoft software.</p>
<p>-- Paris newsroom +331 4221 5452</p>
